Temperature reading was taken and found to be over 280 degrees. Control room operators was contacted to shutdown CV214. Water was used in attempt to cool the equipment down in order to gain access. title: CV204 tail pulley (No 6) suffered 0.5hrs of unplanned downtime to tighten up the bearing adaptor sleeve locknut two days prior to a major shutdown. ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000100
description: During an inspection on 11/07/2018, the pulley was found to be running very close to the structure on the LHS (float side). The RHS (fixed side) bearing endcap was removed and it was noted that the shaft had moved axially from beneath the bearing adaptor sleeve. The pulley shell/shaft was pushed back into its correct location, and the bearing adaptor sleeve lock nut retightened. The shaft slipped beneath the fixed end bearing, causing the pulley to move and take up all the float in the float bearing. Given the shaft moved about 10-15mm, the float end bearing must not have been central in the housing.

title: BN151 GRIZZLY BEAM # 2 REFERENCED FROM REAR ON BIN FAILURE; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000392
description: During NS dated 27/12/2020 Grizzly Beam 2 referenced from BN151 backwall failed in the following manner. Historically two standard grizzly beams were modified during April 2019 to increase the beam cross sectional area in the attempt to increase the beam integrity. Namely grizzly beams 4 & 5. There was an I-Beam like section added to the lower portion of the standard beam and this procedure was carried out during our weekly works. Upon close visual inspection it appears the 10mm fillet fusing the added I-Beam section to the standard beam has not fully penetrated, hence the correct weld procedure is in question. This additive I-Beam section has fractured from the standard grizzly beam and locked into the primary SZ151 and tripped. The N/S maintenance team have trammed out the sizer and crane removed the segment. This process resulted in a 196 - minutes downtime in production.

title: Failure of RHS Locking Element on 12CV203A pulley No 7.; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000029

It was in service for 3.5 years prior to this failure. In the last 3 months of service the conveyor had run at ~2700tph, with a maximum of 2891 tpa. title: Failure of RHS Locking Element on Reclaimer Tail Pulley CV602; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000030
description: On the 12/5/2018 at 2am the Reclaimer boom conveyor tail pulley RHS locking element was found to be œpushed out  from the end disk, and the pulley was changed out with the spare. The failed pulley had been manufactured by Tefco (serial No 4479) and overhauled by Orontide in June 2013. The pulley was installed on 21/2/2014 and was in service for 4.25 years prior to this failure. It took 66hrs to rectify the consequential damage and install the spare pulley. During this period trains were loaded direct from the plant, incurring moderate rate loss. During strip down, all the RHS locking element bolts were found to have failed by fatigue cracking (through the threaded section at thrust ring interface), see Fig 2; and the interface between the tapers was corroded, see Fig 3. The LHS locking element was found to be corroded, but none of the bolts had failed, see Fig 4.

title: CV903 VSD Fan Failure; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 31
description: Root Cause: CV903 VSD fan capacitor failed Secondary Cause: No strategy in place to change out the fan, only the VSD as a kit on 7Y PM02 which has been skipped What We Found: Capacitors have not been a common cause in other VSD fan failures across site This increased the time taken to diagnose this issue as the SCHRACK relay was changed out first The replacement capacitor required was not listed in the BOM The material number we had for the replacement capacitor has been deleted and replaced with a new material number, but this number was not listed under the equipment in the BOM. This was only discovered after enquiring with the cataloguing team From review other VSD BOMs it was found that capacitors were generally not listed, and fans were only listed for some equipment There is no individual replacement strategy in place for the VSD fan, only the VSD module as whole which is on a 7Y PM02 C/O. This was called in 2018 but W/O was cancelled with no comments as to why. It was called again in 2020 but skipped with the next C/O now scheduled to call again in 2027 There is currently work being conducted to review VSD C/O strategies, identify gaps and ensure new strategies are implemented where necessary but had not got to CV903 yet Recommendations: Continue to stock one complete spare VSD module from which spare parts can be taken in a breakdown Add the VSD fan and capacitor as individual items to the BOM with a minimum stock level of zero, to allow for easy reordering of these parts if they have to be taken from the spare VSD module again in the future Review BOMs for all VSDs to ensure all required critical spare parts are listed in the BOM  Replace the capacitor that was taken from the spare VSD module Replace the CV903 VSD in the next shut Implement new VSD & fan C/O strategy to CV903 and other conveyors that have not had the new strategy implemented Investigate a way to ensure necessary PM02 change outs do not get skipped/cancelled when required

title: DT5236 POS 4 Final Drive Failure @ 15006 hrs. Front service brake was not responding to command.; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000306

Previously the slack adjuster had been replaced prior to this failure. After the Pos 4 diagnosis, the truck went down for tray not tipping. The hydraulic tank had low oil and differential was overfilling. Pos 3 was then diagonized as faulty. Both final drives had internal oil bypass into differential were replaced.

title: DT5237 POS 4 Final Drive Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000305
description: DT5237 went down for tray not lifting, very low hydraulic oil level and oil coming out of diff breather due to Diff overfill. Internal bypassing of hydraulic oil into the differential was flagged and POS 3 final drive was deemed to have failed. POS 3 FD was replaced and truck briefly went back to work before it shut down due to low hyd oil level. A fitter noticed that oil was coming out of the differential breather, indicating internal bypass of hyd oil. Further investigation found that the brake cooling pressure was excessively high around 150psi (system pressure at idle is about 25psi max). Pieces of rubber were found to be in the brake cooling screen from what appeared to be an internal hose failure. All brake cooling hoses were inspected and no signs of internal damage were found, indicating the rubber could be from a previous failure. POS 4 Final Drive was deemed to have failed and was changed out. The total downtime occurred between these two component failures was approx. 220 hours. POS 3 was at 13,496 hrs and POS 4 at 11,788 hrs. Planned life is 24,000 hrs.

title: 15SC02 Middle Exciter Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000099
description: On Monday 14/05/2018 it was reported that the middle exciter of 15SC02 was starting to make a small abnormal whining noise. By Friday 18/05/2018, the CONiQ system Bearing Condition Unit (BCU) of the middle exciter was detecting vibration levels in excess of 30 (Hi Hi alarm triggered at 10). The middle exciter was reported as being particularly noisy at start-up and the whining was confirmed as still being present. A decision was made to replace the middle exciter. Preparations were made during the day and OPF1 Module B was shut down at approximately 15:00. The exciter was replaced and approximately 14 hours later the module was brought back online.   Disassembly of the exciter and subsequent bearing failure analysis revealed that bearing œD  (idler shaft fixed bearing side) was in very poor condition with a heavily spalled inner race.

title: WL022 - Final Drive Failures - Jan/Feb 2020; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000262
description: At 8:41PM on Thursday January 16th 2020 at the Christmas Creek Remote Crushing Hub WL022 broke down with reports of oil coming out the top of the brake cooling tank breather. This is an indication of failed service brake piston seal on one of the wheel loaders final drives. The bypassing seal forces higher pressure service brake oil into the brake cooling circuit and raises the level of the brake cooling tank until oil comes out of the breather.   Knowing this, and having had similar failures in the past, the service crew pressure tested each of the final drives ' brake packs in the field to determine that it was the front right (POS 2) final drive that had failed. The component was a Westrac service exchange (SX) component that had completed 7086 hrs of its proposed 22000 hr life (32.2%)

title: WL269 - 994H - POS 3 Final Drive Failure - Brake Passing ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000185
description: Bypassing brake seal on POS3 final drive of WL269.

title: 994H SX Steering Cylinders not making life; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000295
description: A maintenance strategy review (MSR) of 994H steering cylinder lives across the three FMG sites highlighted a large disparity between the service life of new and SX cylinders. New cylinders have an 80% chance of making it to 14 '000 hrs whereas SX cylinders only have an 80% chance of making it to 9 '360 hours.  The failure mode of 90% of failed cylinder is the same: weeping from the rod seals.  This disparity in expected life is the driver for this RCA. There should be no reason a properly rebuilt cylinder shouldn ™t achieve the same average life as new one.

title: Failed Pos 1 Spindle on GR120; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000241
description: At approx. 04:10 GR120 was grading the running track in Lefroy S04 EX7103 dig floor. After the grader had completed the first pass the grader had turned around at low speed to continue grading at this point pos 1 had detached from the machine and came to rest 39m away from the grader.  Mobile maintenance have attended scene and assessed the Pos 1 Spindle of GR120.  A PSR was downloaded by the ancillary inspector and photos were taken of the scene and the failed iron.  With the maintenance program for the spindle there are a few systems in place to monitor the structural integrity of the components as below:  GR120 has had recent NDT Testing on the 20/5/19 and had shown no signs of cracks in the spindle, this is carried out quarterly by the OEM Vendor   ( Evidence attached in documentation ) Oil sample are taken of the bearing during routine servicing. The previous two samples on the bearing prior to failure were both A samples.  New Components will be installed to GR120 & the failed spindle will be sent back to OEM to determine the root cause of the component failure.

title: WL266 POS1 Brake Pack Bypassing; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000338
description: Machine went down at 11:09 AM with the report oil leaking out the top of the brake cooling tank breather on the back deck of the machine. This is a common type of failure on this machine so it was quickly diagnosed by the breakdowns crew that one of the brake piston seals has failed causing brake oil to transfer across into the brake cooling system.   The brake packs were pressure tested and it was determined that the POS1 final drive was not holding pressure and had therefore failed. The component had only completed 273 of planned 22 '000 hour lift (1.25%)

title: CV948 Belt Damage; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 50
description:
Root Cause:
•	Repair pushed out of the PM22OL21 shutdown

Secondary Cause: 
•	CV948/CV922 blocked chute 
•	Delay significantly extended due to bad weather conditions 

What We Found:
•	Notification raised in SAP for CV948 Splice 1 Skive Lifting Hot Repair on 27/03/22
o	Was scheduled into the PM22OL21 shutdown due to estimated job duration being 12 hours
o	SL701 and RC702 were forced into the shutdown. CV948 was visually inspected, and decision made that it was ok to be pushed out of the shut
•	Conducted several visual inspections by various people
o	On 23/5/2022 head chute inspected and noticed spillage outside the chute and on the rails, possibly indicating an overflow from a blocked chute
o	In general, it was all in good condition and the cleaners looked fine. A chipped tooth was noticed.  
•	Blocked chute event was on 29/05/2022 04:38 and 08:54. The belt damage on 29/05/2022 20:12
o	No feedback if Ops got a chance to inspect the belt
o	The splice failure was picked up by a rip switch. Indicating that it progressively worsened after the blocked chute event 
o	Was running FB product over CV948 and the tonnage rate only decreased during the delay time
•	Extended downtime due to bad weather conditions 

Recommendations:
•	Engineering solution to allow belt repair to be conducted more easily 
o	Reduce downtime during bad weather conditions 
o	Portable and easy to manoeuvre

title: CR306 Oil leak from head; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000055
description: On 19/08/18 CR306 tripped out on low lube oil. Approx. 1200 liters of oil was transferred into the lube tank and the crusher returned to service. During NS the crusher tripped out again on low lube oil. It was determined that the crusher was suffering a sever lube oil loss which could not be determined. The crusher was converted to a chute for the remainder of the shift. On 20/08/18 the crusher head was removed and inspected. It was found that an oil seal between the stub shaft and the head had failed causing the oil to bypass out through the stub shaft plate and the lock nut/impact plate joint.

title: TUL603 return overtravel; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 51
description:
Root Cause:
•	One of the relays installed was the wrong type  

What We Found:
•	One of the relays was the wrong type 
o	Prevented bypass button 
o	Pilz relay could not reset 
o	It is run to end of life and was previous changed out after a breakdown 
o	This led to the extended delay before it was recognised that the wrong relay was installed 
•	The overtravel fault alarm is on the main SCADA screen 
•	Overtravel limit circuit design is an electrical design from OEM 

Recommendations: 
•	Continue investigating if it is a genuine overtravel by involving Metsos and supervisors. This is tracked on 8:10 board
•	Verify that the protective device audit (PDA) checks overtravel recovery
o	Highlight the importance with relevant teams 
•	Continue updating drawings to ensure latest revision
•	Investigate the pressure in the grippers because they should not be decreasing

title: CV908 Belt Damage / Scraper ; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 52
description: This RCA investigation has determined that the belt damage of CV908 due to the D3 cleaner incorrect adjustment. The adjustment was conducted correctly as per the tension specification given by Hosch for the D3 cleaner, however Hosch have since advised further procedures including buffing blades and reducing the amount of tension used for worn blades is required. No documentation of these additional procedures/considerations had been supplied by Hosch to FMG at the time the incorrect adjustment occurred. Through engagement with Hosch, an investigation into the lack of formalised written OEM procedure on adjusting the D3 scrapers and lack of understanding around the Iris system was conducted. Resulting in, actions to ensure full procedures for adjusting the cleaners are supplied by Hosch to FMG, there is an increased transparency between Hosch and FMG regarding the D3 scraper trial Hosch to investigate accelerated belt wear on a belt with Hosch equipment.

title: 30TH01 Rake Lift Drive Failure
description:
RCA076 
• At 0920 on 26/2/21, 30TH01 rake was lifted in preparation for start up after OPF1 major 
shutdown.
• Maintenance was called to the asset after subsequent attempts to lower the rake resulted in 
rake drive trips.
• The lift was observed to be driven past the limit switch set points (trends indicated it had 
continued driving) and mechanical inspection revealed damage to the rake lift screw and brass 
acme thread drive. 
• The spare unit was retrieved from store, however the box contained a larger lift from the OPF 2 
thickener. Time to repair was impacted as modifications were executed to fit the screw lift available.

title: CV213 Brake Fault
description:
CV213 brake 3 began intermittently faulting on phase loss.

Initial fault at 4:44 AM was reset and CV213 resumed operation. The brake tripped an additional 2 times before fault finding determined there was an issue with the circuit breaker.

Decision made between operations and maintenance to attempt to continue operating until product change on 17/10/22. A contingency plan put in place to isolate SR508 and swap out faulty circuit breaker if fault reoccurred before product change.

Breaker faulted again at 11:57 AM and electricians called and isolated SR508 for circuit breaker replacement.

New circuit breaker installed and SR508 de-isolated at 1:00 PM and handed back to control.

Approximately 1 hour of additional downtime re-setting the plant due to 415v substation isolation.

description:
Truck went down with a no propel fault 21:41 on 20/08/2022. 
Fitters begun to Investigate LH rear HP turbo, due to oil and coolant coming from related exhaust bellows.
Found damage to fins on exhaust side of turbo, like something has gone through the exhaust manifold and through the turbo.
Removed turbo for further inspection.
Removed LHS rocker covers to inspect for damaged valve assemblies, found nothing obvious.
Removed rocker gear and injectors to investigate further.
Investigated engine failure and found number 2-cylinder head leaking coolant into sump oil , used borescope and found one of the exhaust valves broken and cylinder head damaged.

The rebuilt carousel failed again and was replaced with new new carousel on 27/05/2022 and the rebuilt carousel was sent for warranty.

title: WC014 - Engine Failure ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000506
description: During the investigation process, it was found that a job was carried out on the air intake system. Additionally, various SOS alerts from Westrac lab were raised in conjunction with the CMA Team review. Engine oil samples were showing a normal and steady wear and contaminants trend until September 7th 2021. During the service carried out on September 7th, POS1 turbo housing was found cracked (refer to WO 101586444). This was replaced at the time as proactive action. On September 25th, an engine oil sample came back rated as "action required" for the first time. Westrac lab recommendation was, "The aluminium and silicon indicate possible dirt entry. Check the seals, breathers, induction system and fill point for dirt entry points. Iron is high. Check for wear debris and resample after any adjustments or repairs". The CMA Team also reviewed this sample and raised notification 101752864 on October 5th. The notification was not actioned until November 17th, where filters were replaced and engine oil drained. A second "actioned required" was flagged by Westrac lab as well as the CMA Team with a new notification (101758847). This appeared to be overlooked as no confirmation time was found nor comments of the job performed. A third "actioned required" was sent out by Westrac lab on October 26th. Finally, the lab advised an "URGENT ACTION REQUIRED", and the CMA Team raised a breakdown WO (101633370) as an urgent matter ten days before the failure. Westrac lab comments "Based on 644 hours.The aluminium and silicon indicate possible dirt entry. Check the seals, breathers, induction system and fill point for dirt entry points. The PQ index and iron are high. Chrome is slightly high. Cut the filter open and inspect the media for wear debris and resample after any adjustments or repairs" Comments from the inspections were, "changed out engine oil and filters changed out air filters took engine oil sample inspected for dirt entry found multiple engine oil leaks including from heads and filter housing with the largest leak coming from auxillery drive shaft which appears to be the location of dirt entry into engine raised notification to rectify" WC014 presented engine oil consumption of around 50L on the 25th Nov 2021. Engine oil was topped up again on the 26th with extra 50L due to low engine oil level alarm. WC014 went down on the 27.11.2021 due to low engine oil level alarm and high levels of blow-by . During diagnosis it was found excessive engine exhaust smoke through the rev range and whilst under stall (unburnt fuel and oil). The issue was isolated to the LH bank of the engine, having lower exhaust temps on #2,4,6 Cylinders. It was found POS 3 turbo inlet clamps to be loose and multiple engine oil leaks, including cylinder heads and filter housing, with the largest leak coming from the auxiliary driveshaft. Review of SAP data indicates the engine was at approx. 18500hrs at the time of failure, strategy life is 22,000hrs

title: DR059 Dynaset Failure ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000435
description: Two days (i.e. 24/04/21) prior to the failure, Drill Operators noticed they were not getting dust suppression water flow down the drill hole, however this was quickly fixed by switching off/on the hydraulic flow connection which appeared to ˜restart ™ the pump. Throughout the following two days the dynaset would only operate intermediately, continuously dropping out dust suppression water flow down the drill hole and to the water gun. On the day of the failure (26/04/21), the breakdown fitter was called out for an unrelated issue and was additionally alerted by the Drill Operator of the issue that was present with the dynaset. When the fitter tested the dynaset he confirmed there was no water being produced down the drill hole or through the water gun. After trouble shooting the fitter confirmed via testing that the correct hydraulic flow through the P (hydraulic inlet) and T (hydraulic outlet) ports were present, as such isolated the issue to the water side of the dynaset pump and determined the dynaset had failed. The breakdown fitter then swapped out the failed dynaset with a new part.

description:

• SB215 is scheduled to be relined in CP22OP03 (July 2022), but given the severity of SB214 and SB216, outages were required to replace the critical lifters
• SB214 was taken offline on 08/06 and returned to service 11/06. SB216 was taken offline 12/06 and run back up on 14/06

title: Steering Pump failure ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000372

title: DT192 Pos 4 Turbo Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000513
description: 31/12/2021 High exhaust temperature and only 25-40kPa boost pressure. Was parked up in Maintenance Bay ASAP. Infield team found that the Pos 4 turbocharger had failed and also caused minor damage to the Pos 2 turbocharger. The coolant was drained and both turbochargers were removed. Turbo SMU 8357 hours. Strategy is 11000, so made 75% of expected life. Machine SMU 56607 hours. 1/1/2022 The Pos 2&4 turbochargers were replaced. Blew out intake tubes, replaced air filters and engine oil and filters. Two small pieces of debris were found using a magnet tool in the aftercooler. The machine was determined fine to return to work after passing a stall test.

title: DT196 Position 1 turbocharger failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000424
description: P/N:20R-6651 Parts hours: 6312 Operator found dark smoke and oil in exhaust. Infield technician attended to site and found turbochargers position 1 and 3 had failed. Turbocharger position 1 was taken to workshop for inspection and failure analysis. The failure description is as follows: 1) The turbine wheel and cartridge shaft were not found inside the exhaust housing, they went through the exhaust pipes and could not be found on site. 2) The exhaust housing was covered by oil that came from the inside of the cartridge. 3) The cartridge shaft was snapped on the base of the compressor wheel. 4) The compressor wheel blades were rubbing against the housing except from 1 blade that was fractured. 5) Bearings and cartridge housing were found scratched and they showed material detachment.

EX7102 Failed Swing Gearbox Front; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000491
description: 24.09.2021 00:40:35 After inspecting front swing box for an oil leak the fitter has noticed that the pinion has dropped more then the rear box. On inspection from Liebherr, it appeared the bottom bearing has failed. Before we cleaned it up it looked like the whole bottom of the drive was loose, however, upon closer inspection it was the bearing carrier that failed. After the swing drive was removed, two metal fragments were obtained from the drain hole. The smaller piece (10mm x15mm) appears to be part of the bearing cage or running surface, and the larger piece (35mm x 28mm) is from a blown roller bearing. Visual metal and brass particles are visible in the oil running out of the drain port. The surface of both the swing drive and the chassis had visible markings from where the dowel had impacted and metal fragments had been wedged between the chassis and gearbox. Some metal fragments were still lodged in the mating surface of the gearbox.

title: Liebherr Fleet Coolant Hardness levels; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000464
description: The EX7111 coolant samples came with an C alert with elevated Chloride, TH water hardness, and magnesium levels. It appears, there have been 3 coolant flushes in past for this machine (SMU3738). The sample which had C alert had 990 Fluid hours on it. The comments from Westrac says low-quality water may have been used for top up or chemical contamination. Apparently, this is only occurring on our Liebherr fleet and has started to occur after November 2020 based on the work orders. Another thing that needs to be noted is that we use RECOCHEM/HDD 1000 as coolant instead of PGXL but we have always used this before and haven ™t had issues in past.

title: DR3113- Maspro Trial Rotary Head Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000489
description: On 11/09/2021 at around 08:21 DR3113 lost rotation and further investigations concluded that the rotary head has failed internally. This was a Trial Rotary head from Maspro which had a hardened adaptor to allow force transfer to the casing once the gear and camp move sufficiently on the spindle under extreme shock. It also had a bearing retaining ring instead of the bearing locating surface. The rotation unit was Trailed( CR-11634) in SM due to the Increase number of rotary head failures in Solomon. The Rotary head has achieved only 725 hours.

WL7108 Artic Bearing Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000503
description: At approximately 10am on 26/11/21, the operator called breakdowns channel after hearing an abrupt banging noise. The machine had been operating freely for 4hrs already that shift. The banging sound could be heard when booming down and going forward. WL7108 was placed in breakdown, the breakdown fitters then attended and subsequently diagnosed the top artic bearing to have failed (excessive movement). The machine was then floated back to the workshop where the top artic bearing was further assessed under live testing, the top bearing was confirmed to have at least 10-20mm of vertical movement. The artic bearing was at 71.7% life (14,340hrs).

title: DT150 Engine fuel pump and oil pump failure.; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000056
description: DT150 was called into the workshop to diagnose HP fuel pump intermittent pressure fault. Pump had failed pressure tests and deemed as failure. Pump was replaced as a result. Filters were discovered with metal debris and further investigation was launched.   In the end, damage was discovered on engine oil pump (nearly new), engine oil coolers and pressure relief valve. SZ010 EM02 NDE Bearing Failure
description:
At 1:59 on 10/10/2022, SZ010 EM01 tripped due to current imbalance on phase A of EM01 drive motor.
CCTV of the sizer feed chute at 2:14 shows more sparks which maybe from additional tramp metal going through the sizer
SZ010 was started again
at 2: 20 however, at 2:33, SZ010 tripped due to non drive end shaft bearing temperature high high protection interlock.
On inspection it was confirmed that the bearing temperature being reported was correct (manually checked using a hand held
temperature gun). Max temp 103 Degree C
SZ010 was isolated and EM02 NDE bearing cover removed. No immediate bearing damage was identified however, the inner
bearing seal had deteriorated, and large amounts of soot was found in the inner bearing void.

title: SB214 FIT6149 Oil flow sensor failure
description:
- SB214 FIT6149 Axial bearing oil flow transmitter tripped out on low flow. 
- Transmitter supply was found to be intermittently dropping out.
- Further investigation indicated a supply cable fault.
- Installed temporary cable and transmitter re-energised.
- Measurements taken with testing instruments, and values returning to SCADA indicated more issues were present.
- Testing found a faulty analogue input on the remote plc rack, and a faulty frequency to analogue transmitter.
- Replaced analogue input card on PLC and input into PLC tested healthy.
- Spare transmitter acquired from Solomon. 
Replaced transmitter and values returned to normal. SB214 handed back to operations.

CV112 Drive Motor 4 Failure
description:
• CV112 faulted with EM04 VSD tripping on overcurrent fault.
• Electricians were called to investigate the faulted VSD.
• Electricians inspected VSD for blown fuses or any signs of damage with nothing found.
• At 8.56 Am EM04 VSD was reset and started but VSD faulted on motor phase loss fault.
• EM04 was isolated to inspect and test the motor and the Initial motor test failed.
• Electricians found damaged star point connection in the terminal box located on the opposite side of the motor.
• EM04 was de-coupled and CV112 was setup to run on 3 drive’s.
• CV112 returned to operation with 3 drives and loading capacity capped at 15000 TPH.

DT5369 Engine Failure 66% Strategy Life; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000544
description: On the 20th of March at approximately 8 pm DT5369 experienced level 3 "Low Engine Oil Pressure" alarms. When attended in the pit, maintenance found that the engine oil filters were full of brass. After the filters were replaced the asset received, according to oil commander, 200 L of engine oil on the 21st of March and another 100 L of oil on the 22nd of March before being transferred to the workshop.   When the asset was brought into the workshop on the 23rd of March for inspection, the engine oil pump was removed and maintenance found that the brass bushing had been partially worn away. Maintenance also noted that bearing material was present in the screens. The engine oil pump was determined to be U/S from this inspection, and a new component was hot spot to site and fitted on the 25th of March  After the new oil pump was installed, DT5359 returned to work on the 26th of March and experienced several level 3 "Low Engine Oil Pressure" alarms. When DT5369 returned to the workshop on the 26th of March maintenance noted a loud, usual noise from the engine. On inspection maintenance reported that the crankshaft may have dropped slightly (~2mm) and that the sump contained a significant amount of metal. Following this, maintenance concluded the engine was U/S

title: DT5310 T/C Failure at 15% Strategy Life; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000517
description: On the morning of the 8th of Jan '22 DT5310 torque converter experienced "excessive slippage". The machine was brought into the workshop and team attempted to adjust the pressures. When the pressure adjustment attempt failed a new modulating valve was installed (need to confirm which valve was changed) and subsequent checks revealed that when the lock up is applied the main relief pressure drops. As the maintenance team then believed the torque converter was internally by-passing a scheduled a change out of the component was planned and executed. At this stage more information on the component failure mode is expected when the torque converter arrives at Westrac 's workshop in Guildford. The Site Westrac Customer Service Manager, Craig Piper, has been engaged to discuss whether a standard CAR report will provide sufficient failure information or whether a Westrac Failure Analysis is required

title: DT170 Dropped valve ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000066
description: On 3/7/18 at 22:01, DT170 engine shut down on low coolant level fault.  Inspection identified dropped valves on cylinder #16, damage to cylinder #15, damage to all turbochargers and severe coolant contamination in engine oil.   1. Sequence of events: 3/07/2018 - #16 Injector replaced during step 8 service (WO 100881753) 3/07/2018 16:36:42 - Truck returned to work after step 8 service 21:59:16 - Exhaust temp difference level 2 alarm 21:59:19 - Exhaust temp difference level 2 alarm 21:59:25 - Exhaust temp difference level 2 alarm 22:01:59 Engine coolant level low Level 3 alarm   2. Possible scenario From the information currently available, a possible scenario would be: -  Few seconds before 21:59:16, one of cylinder #16 valve dropped causing damage to the 3 other valves of the cylinder head.  -  Debris from failed valves trapped in the chamber prevented full piston stroke and caused the liner to crack releasing coolant into the chamber. -  Some debris escaped through exhaust port and damaged turbine wheel of turbochargers on even side. -  Some debris escaped through intake port and went into cylinder #15 causing damage to injector tip, head and piston. -  These debris subsequently escaped through the exhaust port and damaged both turbochargers on odd side. -  Engine shut down at 22:01:59, indicating the engine continued to run for at about 1 minute 43 seconds with dropped valve and increasing amount of coolant in oil.

title: LPP38 Motor Down To Earth Fault; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000160
description: A motor and pump was selected for LPP38, The current setup (48kW) was being replaced for a larger pump and motor (70kW) to withdraw more water from that particular bore. The 70kW QN83-8 was inspected and electrically tested in the laydown yard and passed, (see attached Stage 1 sheet) it had 93m of cable attached which was not sufficient length for the bore so the cable was cut for a lengthier one to be attached. It was then mechanically checked by the fitters (see attached pump inspection) which passed, electrical then rejoined motor tails to drop cable and PT100 and re-tested (see cable join attachment) The pump was then taken out into the field and installed at bore LPP38, during commissioning of the bore electrical found a direct short from phase to earth. The pump was then pulled out of the bore, the cable joint was cut to determine where the failure was, the 100m drop cable tested fine, the cable joint tested fine, the motor tails and motor still failed its insulation resistance test. The pump was brought back to the workshop where the motor tails was found to have incisions and damage on them which the failure likely started.

title: PU188 failed turbo; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000224

Fitted new turbo to PU188 and started up to check operation, after approx. a minute a noise was heard coming from the turbo. Pulled the intake hose off and found the turbo had failed the same as previous one. Looking over the engine it was noticed that new turbo saver hoses had been fitted and found that the hoses were orientated incorrect not allowing oil from the engine to the turbo

title: DT054 Starter motor failure ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000455
description: Incident: 3 Fitters were maneuvering DT054 into place to align the front hubs to drain the oil. This is part of the service. The truck was required to be moved and one fitter operated the truck. The truck failed to start when the fitter attempted. The team reconvened on the ground and discussed the use of the starter trolley. Two members left the job to find the trolley and the fitter who was operating decided to bleed the fuel pressure because the fuel tank was at 11%. Upon the return of the 2 team members they attempted to start the truck one more time with success. They reconvened at the front of the truck on the ground and saw the sparks coming from beneath the truck. A whining noise was heard above the idle, a definite confirmation the starter motor was stuck in the engaged position. The lower E-stop was pressed and the truck shut down. One person went to grab the wash down hose and started to wet the area of the starter motors, one person isolated the truck, and one person grabbed the fire extinguisher. Once they were satisfied there was no risk of ignition they reported it to the supervisor.  Contributing factors: Current truck SMU 51848 hours. Starter motors changed out at 50733 hours, 10 April 2021. Starter motor stayed engaged when truck was idling.

title: DT768-Steering Charge Faults; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000361
description: DT768 went down with steering charging faults, inspected, tested brake and steering accumulators and found to be low, set all to 1500 psi, sent truck to see how it went, truck went down again, travel back out to truck, Inspected pump pressures to insect cut in and to pressures and standby pressure. Inspected machine and found accumulators to be low, adjusted and sent back to work then went down for the same fault again. Found the steering eh valve to be bypassing at 15psi per second. AHS have been notified. Went and checked accumulator and pump pressures. 1500psi at all 4 accumulators. 3350psi pump pressure. 2750psi flow amp valve steer relief pressure. E-stopped machine and heard bleed down through diverter valve. Handed to AHS to change component as not Komatsu part. Workshop replaced diverter as requested. Completed steering cals. Moved truck off cal pad to allow DT057 to complete a planning checkout. When reversing truck into V-Drain the steering accumulator lights came on. Got Komatsu PSA to help diagnose. Suspected compensator valve to be faulty. Workshop replaced valve. Fault still there. Completed steer bleed down test without autonomy and with autonomy. Found excessive leakage on AHS side. Suspect component in EH valve to be bypassing. Handed over to nightshift to source part and fit. Replaced entire steering EH valve with second hand unit from outside trucks cage, conducted steering cals and planning without fault. Organised service truck to come and fill up hydraulic oil. Replaced a couple 3 pin amp seal connectors at EH valve. Ran around cal pad again. No faults.

title: DT765 Grid box fire; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000536
description: When inspected DT 765 grid blower motor, diffuser assy and the grids the following happened in the order as stated below. 1. Foreign object entered the fan area and all the fan blades broke off 2. The grids over heated with the lack of air flow 3. The diffuser started to warp and melt from the heat to a point where the diffuser touched the grid next to it creating a spark, flash. 4. This created a ground fault that would exit the truck from the propel mode 5. This was logged on VHMS. It lasted 20 seconds 6. The melted, overheated diffuser aluminum caught fire from the spark. 7. The blower motor was still running at this stage and the remaining fan was sucking air over or away from the diffuser fuelling the fire. 8. An attempt was made to put out the fire with 2 x fire extinguisher bottles but due to the angle when sprayed through the small holes in the Gridbox covers the powder was directed away from the fire and could not be effective. 9. With the previous blower motor failure on the same truck the fan motor was seized solid and could not turn thus could not fuel the fire.

title: DT752 Engine Failure ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000468
description: Engine keeps shutting down for low engine oil pressure. Suspect dilution of engine oil as it has a blown head gasket.  SMU - 48714  Engine SMU - 20,185Hrs  Checked engine oil pressure. Was 40psi @ 750rpm and 75psi @ 1935rpm.  Sampled engine oil and coolant   Sent truck from Lefroy to WTA, but it broke down soon after. Didn 't make it.    Low Eng oil pressure warning. Pressure dropping when oil heats up. Sensor was jumping around decided to replace sensor but didn 't rectify issue. Checked coolant tank and ROS tank and found that they were full to the brim and had a lot of pressure behind it. Suspect leaking coolant or fuel into the ENG oil sump. Oil sample taken.    Truck shut down for Eng gathering 17 fault ,found low coolant and fuel topped up ,VHMS download found body up switch constant fault and low eng oil pressure, inspected oil levels ok sent back to work to monitor.    Drained and filled engine oil and send back to workshop    Check on Insite for faults, unable to communicate with Cense ECM. Screen shot done of fault codes logged.    Removed all r/h bank rocker covers to inspect rocker gear/injector. found broken valve bridge on no 2 inlet valve and also a severely bent push rod.    Removed cam followers and inspected them all appears ok and also checked cam lobes all ok also. job is being referred to cummins for further investigation. email was sent by Rob G to detail all work done so far to

title: Engine failure - No.1 Cylinder ; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000495
description: Pos 3 & 4 turbos have failed due to contamination impact on the turbine wheel    Truck was shutdown for high exhaust temperature differential.  Nightshift had inspected the compressor side of all 4 turbos. All ok.  Ran the truck, and noticed small amount of white smoke coming from the RH exhaust. Checked intake manifold pressures, and found sensor #2 was well down compared to #1.  Removed the turbine outlet bellow and manifold for Pos 3&4 turbos, and found both turbine impellers had been damaged.  Removed all RHS rocker covers to inspect for damage.  Found No.1 cylinder had a broken intake valve bridge, and one of the intake valves was sitting lower than the other. The valve lash also felt excessive.  Refitted rocker covers with 2 bolts only, and refitted walkway covers about turbo intakes/fan.  Exhaust is still removed, and turbine outlet is covered with plastic bags, as the decision was made by Craig to have the truck towed back to the workshop.

title: DT752 Blown head gasket; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000456
description: On 31/05/2021 at 13:07 DT752 stopped production after the tray was stuck in the Up position. A major oil leak was discovered and the truck was removed from Service. After waiting for the float to become available, DT752 was recovered to the workshop from Lefroy on 02/06/2021. Head gasket was discovered to be blown and Cummins on-site technicians were utilised to repair. A notification had been raised on 04/12/2020 which identified the failed cylinder head bolt and requested head removal and bolt replacement with the use of Cummins fitters. This was not actioned until the eventual breakdown in late May 2021. At the time of failure DT752 had seen 19,524 engine hours and 45,334 total SMU hours. DT752 experienced a similar failure on cylinder #14 on 10/09/2020 when the engine had 14,559hrs.

title: DT758 Engine Rocker Arm Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000494
description: On the 2nd of October 2021 DT758 was removed from service for suspected low fuel issues and was noted to be running rough. After refueling the truck and fault finding including load boxing it was discovered that the #2 RHS cylinder fuel injector had failed and the related rocker gear was damaged. Further fault finding is ongoing as the failure of this injector has allowed exhaust gas to enter the fuel supply lines and stop the RHS bank from sending fuel to injectors during operation. Further knock on damage may be present as a result.

title: DT056 Engine Connecting Rod Failure; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000430
description: On 13/04/2021 at 07:36, DT056 was removed from service after a pit technician noticed smoke coming from the exhaust and requested the truck be shut down. After moving the truck to the workshop, further inspection revealed that the #15 connecting rod had failed and ventilated the engine. Following engine replacement, DT056 was returned to service on 20/04/2021 after 176hrs of downtime. At the time of failure, the engine component hours were 10,576hrs.

title: DT5255 Pos 3 Wheel Detached; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000547
description: On 30/05/2022 at 06:06 DT5255 Pos 3 wheel has detached in operation while exiting a corner, causing the truck to stop. The truck was travelling from EX106 to OPF with a payload of 222t.

title: DT223 Early Life Turbo Failures; Historical BMS Id: RCA-0000507
description: On the 10th of Dec 2021 at 0040 DT223 was removed from service to investigate LH boost pressure and exhaust temps. Damage on the compressor wheels of the Position 1 and 2 turbos was found. Both turbos were replaced. The Position 1 turbo had previously failed on 23/10/2021 ahead of it 's replacement schedule. Metal shards and fragments were found throughout the intake.

RC701 BW Fluid Coupling Oil Leak; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 37
description: Root Cause: Fluid coupling BTS plug had no washer installed, was finger tight and the sealing face was not clean Secondary Cause: No FMG rebuild specifications Relying on vendors to repair to “OEM specification” without any understanding of what that is What We Found: It was found that the fluid coupling 866T06 was leaking from the Voith BTS plug It was found that:  No sealing washer had been installed behind the plug  The sealing face on the fluid coupling for the BTS plug was dirty, rusty, pitted & had some kind of sealant/putty applied to it The mating surface were not prepped The plugs were not torqued correctly as they were only finger tight There are no FMG repair specifications for the fluid couplings Vendors just get told to return to OEM standard  Pressure test was not up to OEM standard hence the leak was not picked up during QA/QC It was found that the test pressure was conducted at 2 bar for 30minutes at 15°C OEM is for 2 bar for 8 minutes at 60°C Recommendations: Ensure CAMCO has a good work procedure to follow that is up to OEM standard  There should be sign off points at every point of the rebuild  Update the QA/QC procedure to align with OEM specification As missing plug and leaks in the fluid coupling were not identified  Rotatable rebuild specifications need to be improved to avoid unnecessary downtime Install QA/QC procedure for site that compliments the new rebuild specifications There should be sign off points for the fill angle and tie wires Loaded checks to ensure the current on dual drives is within 5%

title: Sample Station input chain failure; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 38
description: Manual sampling conducted for an extended period Root Cause: Compressed air used to actuate bucket pusher contained excessive water, resulting in diminished function. Secondary Cause: OEM air compressor failed and was replaced with another type of compressor which had no mechanism for extracting moisture. What We Found: The previous compressor had an inbuilt air dryer, so moisture levels were lower. It was found that an air dryer plays a critical role in extracting moisture from the compressor.  This was not considered when the switch to a temporary diesel compressor with no air dryer was made. No functional design specification for the SPF was found during the investigation. So, the importance of an air dryer was not emphasised. There are weekly maintenance checks carried out on the Chainbelt however it was found that there is no official SWI for this process.  Inspection items on Chainbelt lack detail and are open to the interpretation of the person doing the inspection.  No formal process for rectifying faults found during inspections or recording details of completed maintenance. Recommendations: Creating/Updating a functional design specification for continuity of information about how to operate the SPF and what parts are critical, so that the same oversight doesn’t occur in the future. Improve clarity of instructions for how to complete inspections and regular maintenance tasks so that they are completed consistently by all maintainers. Improve reporting following completed maintenance tasks so a record is kept of what has been done. Formalise the process of following up on and capturing rectification works from inspections and ad-hoc maintenance tasks

title: RC701 - Slew Bearing Defect; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 8
description: AP20OL11 WO#201479612 26W MRMP Slew Rack & Pinion Insp RC701 WO#201442770 52W MRMP Inspect Slew Bearing RC701 All the ball and cages were inspected and were all free from visible defects. At the previous inspections, the ball cages were in the same place as before. However this inspection the caged have relocated by approx. 1.5 cages counter clock wise During this inspection the defects discovered in last inspections on the lower race (3 defects) and upper race (1 defect) could not be seen anymore as they were covered by the respective ball over the this position. This revealed other cage gap positions and further defects were found. With the ball cages in a different position, some more defects were found. All detected defects are listed in the spreadsheet above and shown in the picture above. All defects are in the area between 160° and 230°. The flakes in the grease were found in the same area. There is the possibility that in 2016, when the grease change out was done by a 3rd party, a foreign body (small nut) was left in the raceway which got crushed gradually by the slew movement

description: Root Cause: The root cause of the motor winding failure was not determined The delay was extended due to not being able to locate the correctly configured spare motor What We Found: The motor had only been installed for two months at the time of failure The motor was sent to third party for assessment, it was confirmed one of the windings had failed however upon strip down no internal damage was found. Due to the motor being stripped by a third party, an OEM warranty claim could not be processed , this resulted in the root cause failure not being determined. The delay was extended due to not having the correctly configured spare in storage. Upon investigation it was found that a correctly configured spare should be held for both TUL602 and TUL603. Maintenance plans for inspection and motor replacement are correct however they did not prevent failure due to failure occurring after only two months in service. It was noted that some past inspections had not been thoroughly completed.

TUL602 Marshalling Panel MPN04 failure; Historical Sharepoint Port Id 32
description: Root Cause: No installation of din rail screw in end terminals  Secondary Cause: Poor conditions inside marshalling panel due to 40mm diameter hole in the bottom gland plate of the panel What We Found: From a visual inspection of the marshalling panel, it was found that:  There was no din rail screw in end terminals of TUL602 MPN04 which caused backplanes to not be secured together, resulting in marshalling panel failure.  The door seals looked good, cards and clips were seated correctly, backplane had no noticeable damage and cables were all protected.   There was an ingress in panel by a 40mm diameter hole in the bottom gland plate of the panel. Making the inside of the marshalling panel be subject to moisture, humidity, dirt, dust, and debris.  There is a 104W maintenance strategy in place for the marshalling panels however it doesn’t include backplane or end terminals inspection The last 104W maintenance review had “N/A” written for several inspection points that may have identified the missing end terminals or the hole in the bottom of the marshalling panel Recommendations: Audit all marshalling panels on site in the next few shutdowns. This is to ensure they are up to standard.  Check for installation of din rail screw in end terminals, door seals, glands seal, and overall general conditions inside. Ensure that MPN04 gets a din rail screw in end terminal installed. Improve 104W maintenance strategy to include inspection of backplanes and end terminals Clarify why in the recent shut, work order 201951547 had a comment N/A for action 3.0 Important to reiterate the expectations for marshalling panel checks  Have 52W inspections on the panel conditions Creating/Updating a PRT on how to change cards inside the marshalling panel. When changing out cards, should be checking everything is secure and end terminals are right Warning about the impact of disrupting the backplanes

description: CV461 Encoder Failure

title: TLO Sample Station VF532 Stroke Fault
description:
- Intermittent 'Stroke Fault' on VF532 causing the sample station to fault. Fault occurring intermittently over multiple shifts.
- Inspection on vibe feeder at approx 0425am found magnetic coil damaged.
- Supply isolated while replacement coil was sourced from stores.
- Manual samples were collected to allow train to finish loading.
- New coil installed and stroke, trip and sensitivity calibrated. 
- Feed rate of vibe feeder was determined to be too slow so mechanical assisted in setting the air gap to the specifications for this feeder.
- Tested in manual and auto and verified trip setting operated, and feed rate was acceptable.
- Handed back to OC at approx 11:15am.
